{"id":466,"date":"2021-02-15T08:30:00","date_gmt":"2021-02-15T08:30:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?p=466"},"modified":"2021-02-14T14:33:50","modified_gmt":"2021-02-14T14:33:50","slug":"rising-vs-falling-edge-for-timing-in-ac-lgad","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/rising-vs-falling-edge-for-timing-in-ac-lgad\/","title":{"rendered":"Rising vs falling edge for timing in AC-LGAD"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>After my first timing measurement with the TCT, presented in <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/first-timing-measurement-with-tct\/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/first-timing-measurement-with-tct\/\" target=\"_blank\">this post<\/a>, I started to play a little bit with timing in an AC-LGAD installed in the TCT. Playing around with different settings in the oscilloscope I noted that the temporal resolution seems to improve if, instead of using the rising edge, the falling edge is used. I don&#8217;t know if this should be surprising, if it is useful, or whatever, but anyway I want to keep record of this fact. <\/p>\n\n\n<style>.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_6394ab-be .kb-table-of-content-wrap{padding-top:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-right:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-bottom:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-left:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_6394ab-be .kb-table-of-contents-title-wrap{padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_6394ab-be .kb-table-of-contents-title{font-weight:regular;font-style:normal;}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_6394ab-be .kb-table-of-content-wrap .kb-table-of-content-list{font-weight:regular;font-style:normal;margin-top:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;}<\/style>\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Setup description<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The setup for this test is very simple. I placed an AC-LGAD<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference_466_1('footnote_plugin_reference_466_1_1');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference_466_1('footnote_plugin_reference_466_1_1');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_466_1_1\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[1]<\/sup><\/a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text_466_1_1\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\">RSD 1 W4-A -2,5 3\u00d73 100, alias John.<\/span><\/span><script type=\"text\/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip_466_1_1').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text_466_1_1', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'top center', relative: true, offset: [-7, 0], });<\/script> in the TCT and connected it to the oscilloscope without any amplifier, as shown below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/1-6.svg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-467\" width=\"403\" height=\"187\"\/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then I positioned the laser in the region between the four pads, having previously adjusted the focus, and after this I started playing. Below there is a screenshot of the oscilloscope showing the signals from each pad. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-14_13-12-18-1024x664.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-468\" width=\"733\" height=\"475\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-14_13-12-18-1024x664.png 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-14_13-12-18-300x194.png 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-14_13-12-18-768x498.png 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/Screenshot_2021-02-14_13-12-18.png 1282w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 733px) 100vw, 733px\" \/><figcaption>Screenshot of the oscilloscope showing the signal from each of the four pads.<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>I am using the laser splitting system described in <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/laser-delay-system-for-the-scanning-tct\/\" target=\"_blank\">this post<\/a>, that is why there are two pulses separated by 100 ns. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Rising vs falling edge<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>After playing for a while, I used the math functions of the oscilloscope to compute the sum of the four signals:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-mathml-mathmlblock\">\\[ \\text{F3} = \\text{C1} + \\text{C2} + \\text{C3} + \\text{C4}. \\]<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/wp-polyfill-inert.min.js?ver=3.1.2\" id=\"wp-polyfill-inert-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/regenerator-runtime.min.js?ver=0.14.0\" id=\"regenerator-runtime-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/wp-polyfill.min.js?ver=3.15.0\" id=\"wp-polyfill-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/hooks.min.js?ver=c6aec9a8d4e5a5d543a1\" id=\"wp-hooks-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/i18n.min.js?ver=7701b0c3857f914212ef\" id=\"wp-i18n-js\"><\/script>\n<script id=\"wp-i18n-js-after\">\nwp.i18n.setLocaleData( { 'text direction\\u0004ltr': [ 'ltr' ] } );\n<\/script>\n<script  async src=\"https:\/\/cdnjs.cloudflare.com\/ajax\/libs\/mathjax\/2.7.7\/MathJax.js?config=TeX-MML-AM_CHTML\" id=\"mathjax-js\"><\/script>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p> (F3 is the name this quantity was given by the oscilloscope, see pictures below.) I did this to reduce the non-correlated components (i.e. the noise). This sum is basically the &#8220;total signal&#8221;, because in this AC-LGADs it is shared by all the pads so the sum must be approximately equal to the signal without splitting. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>I activated the persistence function in the oscilloscope and zoomed into one of the peaks of this signal, and I noticed this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/2-6.svg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-469\" width=\"720\" height=\"467\"\/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>If we look carefully we note that \\( \\sigma_R > \\sigma_F \\). In regular LGADs we usually measure time by using the rising edge. In this case, however, it seems that it could be better to use the falling edge. This is (probably) related to the fact that this detector is AC coupled.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>I configured a &#8220;Period@level&#8221; measurement for the F3 signal and compared the two scenarios: Rising edge vs falling edge. These are my results:<\/p>\n\n\n<style>.wp-block-kadence-advancedgallery.kb-gallery-wrap-id-_5da9a0-c8{overflow:hidden;}.kb-gallery-type-carousel.kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 .kt-blocks-carousel .kt-blocks-carousel-init{margin:0 -5px;}.kb-gallery-type-carousel.kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 .kt-blocks-carousel .kt-blocks-carousel-init .kb-slide-item{padding:4px 5px;}.kb-gallery-type-carousel.kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 .kt-blocks-carousel .kt-blocks-carousel-init .slick-prev{left:5px;}.kb-gallery-type-carousel.kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 .kt-blocks-carousel .kt-blocks-carousel-init .slick-next{right:5px;}.kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 .kadence-blocks-gallery-item .kb-gal-image-radius{border-radius:0px 0px 0px 0px;}<\/style>\n<div class=\"wp-block-kadence-advancedgallery kb-gallery-wrap-id-_5da9a0-c8\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-ul kb-gallery-type-carousel kb-gallery-id-_5da9a0-c8 kb-gallery-caption-style-bottom-hover kb-gallery-filter-none kb-gallery-magnific-init\" data-image-filter=\"none\" data-lightbox-caption=\"false\"><div class=\"kt-blocks-carousel kt-carousel-container-dotstyle-dark\"><div class=\"kt-blocks-carousel-init kb-gallery-carousel kt-carousel-arrowstyle-whiteondark kt-carousel-dotstyle-dark\" data-columns-xxl=\"2\" data-columns-xl=\"2\" data-columns-md=\"2\" data-columns-sm=\"2\" data-columns-xs=\"1\" data-columns-ss=\"1\" data-slider-anim-speed=\"400\" data-slider-scroll=\"1\" data-slider-arrows=\"true\" data-slider-dots=\"true\" data-slider-hover-pause=\"false\" data-slider-auto=\"false\" data-slider-speed=\"7000\"><div class=\"kb-slide-item kb-gallery-carousel-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item-inner\"><figure class=\"kb-gallery-figure kb-gallery-item-has-link kadence-blocks-gallery-item-hide-caption kb-has-image-ratio-land32\"><a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/3-7.svg\" class=\"kb-gallery-item-link\"><div class=\"kb-gal-image-radius\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-image-contain kadence-blocks-gallery-intrinsic kb-gallery-image-ratio-land32\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/3-7.svg\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" alt=\"\" data-full-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/3-7.svg\" data-light-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/3-7.svg\" data-id=\"471\" data-link=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?attachment_id=471\" class=\"wp-image-471 skip-lazy\"\/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"kb-slide-item kb-gallery-carousel-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item-inner\"><figure class=\"kb-gallery-figure kb-gallery-item-has-link kadence-blocks-gallery-item-hide-caption kb-has-image-ratio-land32\"><a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/4-3.svg\" class=\"kb-gallery-item-link\"><div class=\"kb-gal-image-radius\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-image-contain kadence-blocks-gallery-intrinsic kb-gallery-image-ratio-land32\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/4-3.svg\" width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" alt=\"\" data-full-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/4-3.svg\" data-light-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/02\/4-3.svg\" data-id=\"472\" data-link=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?attachment_id=472\" class=\"wp-image-472 skip-lazy\"\/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Taking into account that both pulses are &#8220;statistically identical&#8221; and assuming that the fluctuations are only due to intrinsic effects from the AC-LGAD, the time resolution is the standard deviation over sqrt(2), i.e.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-mathml-mathmlblock\">\\[ \\left\\{ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\sigma_{\\text{AC-LGAD}}^{\\text{Rising edge}}=44.5\\text{ ps}\\\\\n\\\\\n &amp; \\sigma_{\\text{AC-LGAD}}^{\\text{Falling edge}}=32.9\\text{ ps}\n\\end{aligned}\n\\right. \\]<\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>By using the falling edge instead of the rising edge there is an improvement of 25 % in this time resolution for this AC-LGAD. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Open question<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Consider a regular LGAD, not an AC-LGAD. What is better, to couple to it in DC as we usually do<span class=\"footnote_referrer\"><a role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" onclick=\"footnote_moveToReference_466_1('footnote_plugin_reference_466_1_2');\" onkeypress=\"footnote_moveToReference_466_1('footnote_plugin_reference_466_1_2');\" ><sup id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_466_1_2\" class=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text\">[2]<\/sup><\/a><span id=\"footnote_plugin_tooltip_text_466_1_2\" class=\"footnote_tooltip\">See e.g. <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/first-timing-measurement-with-tct\/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/first-timing-measurement-with-tct\/\" target=\"_blank\">this post<\/a> and <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/strange-bipolar-current-pulses-in-pin-diode-with-beta-source\/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/strange-bipolar-current-pulses-in-pin-diode-with-beta-source\/\" target=\"_blank\">this post<\/a>.<\/span><\/span><script type=\"text\/javascript\"> jQuery('#footnote_plugin_tooltip_466_1_2').tooltip({ tip: '#footnote_plugin_tooltip_text_466_1_2', tipClass: 'footnote_tooltip', effect: 'fade', predelay: 0, fadeInSpeed: 200, delay: 400, fadeOutSpeed: 200, position: 'top center', relative: true, offset: [-7, 0], });<\/script> or instead change to an AC coupling and exploit this effect? Still don&#8217;t know. It may happen that adding the AC coupling degrades the time resolution in such a way that the improvement after using the falling edge is not enough to compensate such degradation. Or not.<\/p>\n<div class=\"speaker-mute footnotes_reference_container\"> <div class=\"footnote_container_prepare\"><p><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_label pointer\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container_466_1();\">References<\/span><span role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" class=\"footnote_reference_container_collapse_button\" style=\"display: none;\" onclick=\"footnote_expand_collapse_reference_container_466_1();\">[<a id=\"footnote_reference_container_collapse_button_466_1\">+<\/a>]<\/span><\/p><\/div> <div id=\"footnote_references_container_466_1\" style=\"\"><table class=\"footnotes_table footnote-reference-container\"><caption class=\